{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772061150,"nonce":"1XEjIJxcX/ZEu4NUWPKbezwCkEw=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87sMz8V","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/261#issuecomment-3962781461"},"message":"The structure `layers/main/{distro}/core_ws` (and other workspace layers) slots in cleanly without disrupting the existing hierarchy. Each distro subtree would be a complete, independently sourceable workspace with its own `build/`, `install/`, and `log/` directories, giving natural build isolation.\n\nUsing distro-named branches in the manifest repo (`jazzy`, `kilted`, `rolling`) follows established ROS ecosystem convention and makes the intent clear. Each branch describes the appropriate `.repos` for that distro, pointing to distro-specific branches of upstream packages as appropriate.\n\nThe three distros serve somewhat different purposes in practice:\n- **jazzy** — maintenance/backport target; updates when explicitly ported from kilted\n- **kilted** — primary active development, e.g. taking advantage of the updated depthai-ros API and evolving ROS 2 patterns\n- **rolling** — upstream contribution target; packages here may need fork remotes configured for PRs, not just upstream references\n\nThat last point is worth being intentional about in the manifest: rolling entries for packages you're contributing to would need your fork as the remote, while dependency-only packages can just reference upstream rolling branches.\n\nImplementation would involve: adding the distro path convention to the workspace structure, distro-named branches in the manifest repo, updating init/update tooling to accept a distro argument, and extending agent context so agents know which distro subtree they're operating in.\n\n---\n*Comment drafted with assistance from Claude Sonnet 4.6 (Anthropic)*","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772205225,"nonce":"is8rBB2H4nB1gLdLMuhYvbxsm34=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87s1mjk","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/261#issuecomment-3973474532"},"message":"## Review\n\n### Scope Assessment\n\n**Well-scoped?** No — this is a significant architectural change that touches nearly every workspace subsystem (directory structure, `env.sh` sourcing, worktree scripts, manifest repo branching, build tooling, agent context). A single PR would be very large and hard to review. Consider breaking into sub-issues:\n\n1. **ADR + directory convention** — decide and record the `layers/main/{distro}/` structure\n2. **Manifest repo branching** — distro-named branches with per-distro `.repos` files\n3. **`env.sh` / `build.sh` updates** — accept a distro argument, source the right subtree\n4. **Worktree tooling** — extend `worktree_create.sh` to accept `--distro`\n5. **Agent context** — expose `$ROS_DISTRO` or similar so agents know which subtree they're in\n6. **`ARCHITECTURE.md` / docs updates** — reflect the new structure\n\nEach of these is a reviewable, independently testable unit.\n\n**Right repo?** Yes — this is workspace infrastructure, not project-specific content.\n\n**Dependencies**: The manifest repo will need parallel changes (distro-named branches). The `setup.sh` bootstrap flow will need updating. Both Pattern A and Pattern B manifest configurations need consideration.\n\n### Principle Alignment\n\n| Principle | Status | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Human control and transparency | OK | Issue is clear about intent; owner comment adds good detail on distro roles |\n| Enforcement over documentation | Watch | The new distro dimension will need enforcement — agents should not accidentally cross-source distros. Consider a guardrail in `env.sh` |\n| Capture decisions, not just implementations | Action needed | This is a major architectural decision. An ADR should be written before implementation begins, covering: directory convention, manifest branching strategy, and how rolling forks are handled |\n| A change includes its consequences | Watch | The consequences are extensive — every script that references `layers/main/` will need updating. The sub-issue breakdown above helps ensure nothing is missed |\n| Only what's needed | Watch | The issue proposes three distros (jazzy, kilted, rolling). Consider whether all three are needed at launch or if starting with two (jazzy + kilted) and adding rolling later would reduce initial complexity |\n| Improve incrementally | Action needed | This should be decomposed into incremental sub-issues rather than delivered as one large change |\n| Workspace vs. project separation | OK | This is pure workspace infrastructure |\n| Workspace improvements cascade to projects | OK | Multi-distro support benefits all projects using the workspace |\n\n### ADR Applicability\n\n| ADR | Triggered | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0001 — Adopt ADRs | **Yes** | A new ADR is needed for the multi-distro architecture decision (directory convention, manifest branching, distro selection mechanism) |\n| 0002 — Worktree isolation | **Yes** | Worktree scripts will need a `--distro` parameter; the worktree path structure may change |\n| 0003 — Project-agnostic workspace | Yes (positive) | Multi-distro support makes the workspace more generic, aligning well with this ADR |\n| 0004 — Enforcement hierarchy | **Yes** | Cross-distro contamination should be prevented at multiple layers (env.sh guardrail, build script validation) |\n| 0005 — Layered enforcement | Watch | New enforcement points should follow the layered pattern |\n| 0006 — Shared AGENTS.md | Watch | `AGENTS.md` references `layers/main/` paths that will change |\n\n### Consequences\n\nItems that should be updated as part of this work (per consequences map):\n\n- `ARCHITECTURE.md` — directory structure diagram, source order, layer descriptions all reference the current flat structure\n- `AGENTS.md` — worktree workflow section, layered architecture diagram, build commands\n- `.agent/WORKTREE_GUIDE.md` — path conventions\n- `.agent/scripts/env.sh` — sourcing logic\n- `.agent/scripts/build.sh` — layer iteration\n- `.agent/scripts/worktree_create.sh` / `worktree_enter.sh` — path construction\n- `.agent/scripts/setup.sh` — bootstrap flow\n- `Makefile` — build/test targets\n- `configs/manifest` symlink strategy — may need per-distro symlinks or a single multi-distro config\n\n### Recommendations\n\n1. **Write an ADR first** — this is the most impactful architectural decision since the layered workspace was established. Record the directory convention, manifest branching strategy, and distro selection mechanism before coding.\n2. **Decompose into sub-issues** — the owner's comment already outlines a natural breakdown. Creating tracked sub-issues would make incremental delivery concrete.\n3. **Start with two distros** — jazzy + kilted covers the immediate need (maintenance + active development). Rolling has additional complexity (fork remotes) that can be a follow-up.\n4. **Design the `env.sh` interface early** — `source env.sh --distro kilted` or `ROS_DISTRO=kilted source env.sh` — this choice cascades through all other tooling.\n5. **Consider backward compatibility** — existing worktrees and the current single-distro setup should continue working during the transition, or there should be a clear migration path.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}